The article discusses the commemoration of the 25th anniversary of the bombing of the Argentine-Israelite Mutual Association (AMIA) community center in Buenos Aires, Argentina by Hizballah, an Iranian proxy designated as a Foreign Terrorist Organization by the United States. The bombing, which was coordinated by Salman Raouf Salman, resulted in the death of 85 innocent civilians and injured hundreds more, making it the deadliest terrorist attack in Argentina's history. The United States, along with its counterterrorism partners from around the world, gathered at the Western Hemisphere Counterterrorism Ministerial in Buenos Aires to remember the victims and renew their commitment to jointly combat terrorism and its enablers. The article also mentions President Donald J. Trump's promise to preserve the safety and security of the United States and its citizens, and the ongoing efforts to strengthen regional counterterrorism capabilities and enhance cooperation to identify and disrupt terrorist threats and networks worldwide.